  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "The highest and lowest price levels formed during the Asian, London, and New York trading sessions. These levels act as intraday liquidity pools, used to frame the daily narrative, draw liquidity, or identify potential reversal points.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify the start and end times of the specific trading session (e.g., Asian, London, New York).",
    "Mark the highest price (high) and lowest price (low) of the Asian session (approx. 20:00–00:00 EST) as Asia high and low.",
    "Mark the highest and lowest price of the London session (approx. 02:00–05:00 EST) as London high and low.",
    "Mark the highest and lowest price of the New York session (approx. 08:30–11:00 EST) as New York high and low.",
    "Draw horizontal lines on the chart at these price levels for future reference."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Session highs and lows serve as liquidity targets and reversal zones. Price often sweeps one session's level before moving to another, providing draw-on-liquidity objectives. They help frame intraday bias and entry areas, such as looking for reactions at London high/low before targeting Asia high/low. Also used as profit targets and to identify liquidity grabs.",
